<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n06040g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n06" href="#n06040g">N06 (VI.B.11)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n06all.htm#n06040g"> 40(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> dead tired walking but play / tired of play, sleep</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Des enfants qui sont <mark>fatigu&eacute;s lors d&apos;une promenade</mark>, au point de n&apos;avancer plus qu&apos;avec d&eacute;plaisir, savent parfaitement se servir de leurs jambes d&eacute;j&agrave; lasses, d&egrave;s qu&apos;il s&apos;agit de jouer. Bien plus, on pourrait dire que les enfants jouent toute la journ&eacute;e, sans en excepter souvent les heures du repas, jusqu&apos;&agrave; ce qu&apos;<mark>ils s&apos;endorment le soir, <i>fatigu&eacute;s par le jeu</i></mark>. <font color="green">[Children who are tired during a walk, to the point of advancing more than with displeasure, know perfectly well how to use their already tired legs, as soon as it is a question of playing. Even more, we could say that children play all day long, without often excepting the hours of the meal, until they fall asleep at night, tired by the game.]</font> <small> Fr&eacute;d&eacute;ric Queyrat, <a name="FQLJ" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#FQLJ"><cite title="source">Les Jeux des Enfants</cite></a> (1920) 32</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
